
                         DOS/4G RELEASE NOTES
                         --------------------

                       +----------------------+
                       | Key to release notes |
                       |                      |
                       | E -- Enhancement     |
                       | B -- Bug (fix)       |
                       | D -- Documentation   |
                       +----------------------+


Release 2.60, April 25, 1997 (changes since internal release 2.50)
------------------------------------------------------------------

E ** The upper words of the EBX, EBP, ESI and EDI registers are saved and
     restored during DOS calls, to prevent badly-behaved protected-mode
     device drivers (etc.) from crashing Watcom library functions.

E ** The maximum number of allocation handles has been increased from 16K
     to 64K - 1, increasing the total amount of memory that can be allocated
     as 1-page blocks to 256 MB (from 64 MB).

E ** Old-style option-setting syntax (obsolete option names, section names
     and delimiters, options which take no values) will now be accepted as
     well as current option-setting syntax.

B ** The StartupBanner option now defaults to ON for DOS/4GW and DOS/4GW
     Professional.  In addition, the option value now prints correctly when
     PrintConfig is ON.

E ** The CrashVerbose option now defaults to ON for all three products.

E ** DOS/4GW and DOS/4GW Professional have been modified to allow the 
     debugging options [DOS4G] PrintConfig, SegexeVerbose, LinexeVerbose
     and Verbose and [DOS4GW] VMVerbose (this last is a bug fix).

B ** WVMM.EXP has been modified so that swap_max can't be larger than 
     vmVirtSize (the swap table can't be larger than the total memory space),
     which prevents a GP fault due to trying to search past the end of an
     internal table.  (This would cause a "deinitializing twice" error).

B ** WVMM.EXP has been modified so that allocation handles are correctly
     released and re-used, which prevents VMM from exhausting its memory
     and being unable to allocate any memory at all after a period of time.

B ** The maximum virtual memory size for DOS/4GW Professional has been 
     increased from 64M to 128M (the documented amount).

E ** The default virtual memory size for DOS/4G has been changed from 16M to
     the maximum of twice the available physical memory and 16M; enabling 
     virtual memory on a machine with more than 16M of physical memory will 
     no longer decrease the amount of memory your program can use by default.

B ** Setting the maximum virtual memory size will now take effect even if you
     do not change the default swap size; previously, you had to increase the
     maximum swap size as well as the virtual memory size in order to actually
     get more memory.

B ** DOS/4G programs built with Microsoft will now load successfully in a
     Windows NT DOS box.

E ** The system() and spawn() functions are now supported in DOS/4G programs
     built with Microsoft.

E ** Runtime library functions can now be called from inside DOS/4G DLLs built
     with Microsoft.

B ** DOS/4G programs built with Microsoft will now load into the D32 debugger
     in a Windows NT DOS box.  (This is a separate and independent bug fix -
     a different thing was wrong in the NT DOS box than in the 95 DOS box.)

B ** DOS/4G programs built with Microsoft will now load into the D32 debugger
     in a Windows 95 DOS box.

B ** DOS/4G programs built with Microsoft now copy the environment correctly
     when running under straight DOS; formerly the environment was copied
     incorrectly in a way that sometimes prevented the program from loading
     successfully and always resulted in corrupt environment information being
     available to the program.  (Load failures got an "error R6009" message.)



Release 2.50, , 1996 (changes since release 2.01a)
---------------------------------------------------------

E ** A PE executable loader and the ability to build DOS/4G extended 
	applications with the Microsoft Visual C/C++ Version 4.0 and 4.1 
   compilers has been added to DOS/4G.  Please read the additonal 
   manual pamphlet which came with your v2.50 release disks for 
   directions on how to build PE applications.
   	A number of new files are shipped on the disk to accomadate the
   new MSVC4.x support:
   		PED32API.DLL : PE DLL of D32 API.
         PED32API.LIB : Import library for PED32API.DLL.
         KERNEL32.DLL : Replacement KERNEL32.DLL.
         PE2DBG.EXE	 : Creates DBG and DBL files for PE executables.
         W32PATCH.EXE : Signature byte modifyer; PE<->PX, NE<->DX. Used
         					to allow our loader to get control under Win95 
                        and NT when running unbound applications.
         PESTUB.EXE   : PE specific stub built with MSC8.0.
      The examples have all been updated to be buildable with MSVC4.x.
         
B ** F7 and F9 now work correctly when running D32 in a Windows95 DOS box.

Release 2.01a, April 3, 1996 (changes since release 2.01)
---------------------------------------------------------

B ** The int33 fix below has proven to be unstable and therefor the changes
	have been backed out.
   

Release 2.01, Feb 23rd, 1996 (changes since release 2.01)
--------------------------------------------------------

D ** It was not noted in the 2.00 release.doc that the return value for 
     D32DosMemAlloc changed from 1.97 to 2.00. The returned value is now
     a low memory paragraph segment and not a linear address.

D ** There are two errors in the DOS/4G Family Programmer's Guide, page G4-13.
     There can be no embedded new line (\n) characters in an option string,
     and the colon after SwapFileName must be an equal sign.
     The example should read:
      char DOS4GOPTIONS[]=
           "dos4gvm=VirtualMemory:ON,"
           "SwapFileName=%SWAPFILENAME%\n";

E ** Fixed: D32 can now debug DOS/4G applications in a Windows 95 DOS box.
     There is a Windows 95 bug which prevented exception 1 trapping for 
     which we have implemented a solution.
     
E ** Configuration error reporting has been enhanced. It now prints a pointer
     to the location of the error with approximate options string content.

E ** All relevant examples are now built with Watcom 10.5.

E ** The D32 API was still using the old form (pre-Watcom 10.5) cdecl. This 
     allowed EBX to possibly be trashed during a cdecl function call when 
     using Watcom 10.5. The cdecl decleration in DOS32LIB.H has been 
     modified to default to the new form.
     
E ** The Watcom specific D32 API is built with Watcom 10.5 now.

B ** Fixed: A bug in our DPMI INT 31h/0800h caused mappings of 4MB or greater
     to be misaligned.
     
B ** Comment and blank lines in .ini files were causing problems as were 
     some other .ini formats. Generally an erronious error 4004 was occuring. 
     .INI file processing has been improved to fix these problems.
                     
B ** Configuration error numbers (400x) conflicted with GLU error numbers. 
     These have been changed to 500x.

     Configuration Processing Errors
     -------------------------------
     DOS/4G error (5000): cfg syntax error - Invalid value 
     DOS/4G error (5001): cfg syntax error - Invalid Section
     DOS/4G error (5002): cfg syntax error - Zero length option string
     DOS/4G error (5003): cfg syntax error - Invalid option string
     DOS/4G error (5004): cfg syntax error - Invalid char after option string

B ** The default protected mode int 33 vector installed by DOS/4G
     had been modified in such a manner as to cause a zero vector to be 
     installed in protected mode when no real mode mouse driver was detected. 
     This behavior has now been fixed. If either a zero vector real mode 
     driver or a RET-only real mode handler is detected by DOS/4G then a
     RET-only protected mode handler is installed. If a seemingly valid
     real mode handler is detected then the default protected mode int 33
     translation handler is installed and any int 33 will be chained to
     the real mode handler after translation.

B ** Fixed: When the DOS/4G NullPtrCheck option was turned ON during explicit
     loading of DLLs using D32LoadModule, it resulted in an erroneous
     exception 1 trap inside the linexe loader.

B ** Fixed: A low memory int21/3f (Read From File With Handle) failure which 
     occured under certain conditions. 

B ** Fixed: A bug which caused environment variables as values for 
     configuration options to fail.

B ** Fixed: Several blank lines followed by a ^Z in an .INI file was
     causing the configuration processor to fail. 

B ** Fixed: D32LoadModule was expecting D32DosMemAlloc to return a
     linear address instead of a low memory paragraph segment.

B ** Fixed: DLL entry point resolution now does checking of already loaded 
     modules' modulenames to try and find a match before looking for a 
     matching module file name. Previously, resolution of entry points was
     being done solely by file name and already loaded modules with matching
     module names were being ignored.

Release 2.00, Nov 20th, 1995 (changes since release 1.97)
---------------------------------------------------------

D ** The manual has been dramatically enhanced since version 1.97. There
     are now two manuals (The DOS/4G Family Programmer's Guide and The
     DOS/4G User's Manual) and overall size has increased by about 50
     percent. A brief list of the more important changes and corrections
     follows:

      * Detailed instructions on how to compile, link and debug a
        DOS/4G application with specific compilers have been enhanced.

      * An additional section describing in detail how to build DLLs
        with specific compilers has been included.

      * Corrections to using the embedded option settings, as well as
        specific examples on how to use these options, have been added.

      * Some of the Library Functions have been corrected and updated.
        Several new functions have also been documented.

      * Many new chapters have been added to provide as much information
        on protected-mode programming for the DOS/4G family as possible.

D ** The Kernel option NullPtrCheck still is not supported under an
     external DPMI host.

E ** Configuration has been enhanced for flexibility and consistency
     across the DOS/4G Family of products. Most of the options have
     remained the same.  Please review chapter 4 of the the DOS/4G Family
     Programmer's Guide for details.
     Note: The new format for configuration options is not backwards
     compatible with the 1.97 version configuration options. You must
     convert your preexisting options to the new format or they will
     not work.

E ** D32 now supports structures!  However, there are some limitations.
     You cannot get structure information if you use GLU as your linker.
     At this time, this option is only available to programs compiled and
     linked with Watcom's compiler and linker. Refer to the D32 chapters
     in the documentation for more details.

E ** We now supply a DLL startup object file for Watcom users.  The files
     DLLSTRTS.OBJ [stack-based] and DLLSTRTR.OBJ [register-based] are in
     \dos4g\bin.  Refer to the new documentation in Chapter 3 of the DOS/4G
     Family Programmer's Guide for more information.

E ** The D32 API has been logically broken down from one object module into
     many smaller modules to allow smaller linkage if using only a limited
     subset of the D32 API functions.

E ** There are several new API functions, which are listed below.  See
     Chapter 1 in the DOS/4G User's Manual for more information.

      D32CreateSegAlias
      D32DPMIRmGetVector
      D32DPMIRmSetVector
      D32DPMIPmGetVector
      D32DPMIPmSetVector
      D32LinearToReal
      D32MemStrategy
      D32NamedDescAlloc
      D32PreparePSP
      D32QueryModuleFilename
      D32QueryModuleHandle
      D32QueryModuleName
      D32QueryModuleUsage
      D32QueryProcAddr
      D32RealToLinear
      D32SegMoveLow
      D32TsrExit
      D32TsrSaveIOState
      D32TsrSetIOState
      D32TsrSwitchIOState

E ** You can now load extended segmented executables and DLL's [NE format]
     with DOS/4G.

E ** Support has been implemented for 32-bit arguments to int 21h functions
     48h(allocate), 49h(free), and 4Ah(resize).

E ** WC2DBG can now handle significantly larger executables.

E ** DPMI int 31h 0800h & 0801h physical address mapping calls can now handle
     mappings up to 64MB.

E ** A register-based version of the D32 API library for Watcom, DOS32WCR.LIB,
     is now provided along with the default stack-based library, DOS32WC.LIB.

E ** Examples are now provided in the EXAMPLES subdirectory.

E ** Stack checking has been turned off for all D32 API Libraries for greater
     flexibility.

E ** D32LoadModule now accepts paths with UNIX-style forward slashes.

E ** Processing speed for int 21h has been improved.

E ** Processing speed for int 31h under VM has been improved.

E ** PMINFO32 is now built on the same loader that DOS4G.EXE uses.

E ** PMINFO32 has been enhanced to give more accurate results on newer
     systems.

E ** The kernel's machine identification strategy has been upgraded to better
     recognize some newer systems.

E ** The information displayed when the PRINTCONFIG option is enabled has
     been enhanced.

E ** Some VM changes have been implemented:

     o The swapfile will not grow beyond the SwapMax actual max reported in
       the VM options section if PRINTCONFIG is enabled;

     o Several blatant logical configuration errors now result in the report
       of a fatal error and DOS/4G will terminate execution;

     o If the actual physical memory available to VM is greater than the
       PhysNoVM option, a printout of relevant options will occur if the
       PRINTCONFIG option is enabled.

E ** The stub program may now be built by the Watcom 16-bit compiler, as well
     as the Microsoft compiler.

B ** A problem which caused "DOS/4G error(2511) : swap out error[2]" has been
     fixed.

B ** A failure when there is more than 64MB of RAM present has been fixed.

B ** A problem using INT 21h/67h (grow handles) in the Linexe loader that
     caused access to DLLs to fail under VM has been fixed.

B ** You can now unload a second instance of a DLL without causing the DLL to
     completely unload.

B ** There was a problem with the environment variables LIBPATH and LIBPATH32.
     If you had a '..\' at the begining of your DLL path, the search failed.
     This has been fixed.

B ** Using an Environment Variable with the [dos4g-global] section in a .INI
     file was broken.  This has been fixed.

B ** DOS/4G extended TSRs under 4DOS are now fully supported.

B ** Memory loss problems with the zero-based Linexe loader have been fixed.

B ** Non-linexe symbols are now relocated in the debugger without crashing.

B ** You can now load an exactly-64k segment from a segmented executable file.

B ** A segmented executable .DLL initialization function calling problem has
     been fixed. It now initializes correctly.

B ** Fixed a fast PSP switching problem with some versions of DOS, under VM.

B ** Fixed a problem under VM where the memory report would show that physical
     pages are greater than the virtual space.

B ** Fixed the mouse32 handler to ignore a Microsoft Windows DOS box bug
     which mangles the high word of ESP.

B ** Fixed a problem which prevented the DOS4GOPTIONS string from being
     found in an executable with a large number of exports plus imports.

B ** Fixed problems relating to the use of '.' as the path specification with
     Novell networks, (e.g. DOS4G-VM.SWAPNAME=.).

B ** Fixed a bug in D32ExtAvail which could have resulted in a garbage return
     value (MEMINFO structure would still be updated correctly though).

B ** Fixed a bug which caused EDX and EBX to be swapped after an NMI.

B ** Fixed a linexe loader bug which caused a GPF if trying to use
     D32LoadModule to load a Metaware DLL.

B ** Fixed an accounting bug located in the VM code for handling int 31h/0502h;
     evidenced by an apparent loss of free pages as reported by int 31h/0500h
     or D32MemInfo when doing repeated MALLOCs and FREEs under VM.

B ** Fixed an accounting bug in the VM code for handling int 31h/0503h.

B ** Fixed an int 21h/4Ah resize bug.

B ** Fixed and enhanced the protected mode critical error handler to only
     allow valid choices.

B ** The 4GRUN example has been changed to reflect the fact that the three
     open("con"... statments are only necessary under the Metaware compiler.

B ** A VM accounting bug which occured when spawning has been fixed.

B ** Int 31h functions 050Ah, 0702h, and 0703h now work correctly under VM.


                      KNOWN BUGS AND LIMITATIONS
                      --------------------------

                      +------------------------+
                      | Key to Bugs/Limitations|
                      |                        |
                      | A -- API Functions     |
                      | C -- Configuration     |
                      | O -- OS/Environment*   |
                      | M -- Miscellaneous     |
                      +------------------------+

*See common.doc for more OS/Environment limitations

A ** D32NamedDescAlloc observes the restrictions of DPMI function 000Dh, which
     it invokes.  Thus, it is available only under an external DPMI host.  When
     available, it may be used only with the lowest 16 selectors (range
     04h-7ch).  Protected-mode TSRs should not use this function.

A ** D32RelocateAddress and D32UnrelocateAddress are incompletely described
     in the DOS/4G User's Manual.  The first argument to each function is the
     address of a 16:32 far pointer.  For D32RelocateAddress, the argument is
     the address of a link map address; the function returns in the same
     variable the corresponding run-time address.  For D32UnrelocateAddress,
     the argument is the address of a run-time address; the function returns
     in the same variable the corresponding link map address.  Example:

     FarPtr32 fp32;
     // pass run-time address
     fp32.sel = getcs();
     fp32.off = some_func;
     if (!D32UnrelocateAddress(&fp32,hdl))
      ... error ...
     else
      // success, returns with link map address in fp32
          if (!D32RelocateAddress(&fp32,hdl))
            ... error ...
          else
            // success, returns with run-time address in fp32

A ** D32TsrSwitchPSP and D32TsrSetPSP correctly reset the PSP real-mode
     segment.  DOS function 51h (Get PSP Segment) will reflect this change.
     However, it should be noted     that in the DOS/4G implementation of DOS
     function 62h (Get PSP Address), contrary to the statement in the manual,
     the PSP real mode segment returned by DOS is converted to a protected
     mode selector; furthermore, the protected-mode PSP selector returned by
     DOS function 62h will not change after a call to D32TsrSwitchPSP or
     D32TsrSetPSP.

A ** The D32 API header file DOS32LIB.H presently uses the pre 10.5 Watcom
     definition of cdecl which does not preserve the EBX register during
     function calls. If you are using Watcom 10.5 please read Getting Started
     (ch-9) issue #8 of the Watcom documentation for a desciption of how
     to modify the cdecl pragma in DOS32LIB.H for 10.5 Watcom compatibility.
     Also be aware that the D32 API libraries for Watcom are built with the
     pre 10.5 version cdecl format and therefore any calls to the functions
     in these libraries will not preserve EBX either.

C ** When the embedded options method of DOS/4G configuration is used in con-
     junction with Watcom register-based argument passing conventions (default
     method, or explicitly selected by a /3r, /4r, or /5r compiler option),
     the compiler prefixes an underscore to the exported text string name
     DOS4GOPTIONS.  Therefore in this case, since DOS/4G searches only for
     DOS4GOPTIONS, the EXPORT statement for the link script (either WLINK or
     GLU) must be
          export DOS4GOPTIONS=_DOS4GOPTIONS
     In all other cases, the statement is simply
          export DOS4GOPTIONS
     See EXAMPLES\HELLO\MAKEFILE for an illustration of this.

C ** The configuration option GDTSize does not actually affect the size of
     the GDT itself.  It modifies internal values used by the DOS/4G
     implementation of DOS allocation functions to determine the maximum
     number of selectors that may be allocated.

C ** Multiple semicolon-separated paths may be specified for DLLPATH or
     DLL32PATH, following the DOS PATH method.  They are searched in the order
     in which they occur in the configuration path option.  Example:
          DLLPATH=c:\dll;d:\myapp;e:\misc_dll
     In this example, the specifed subdirectories on drives c:, d:, and e:
     will be searched in sequence until the required DLL is located.

C ** Syntactic errors in configuration switches, as well as contradictory
     settings (such as PHYSMIN > PHYSMAX), will cause execution of DOS/4G to
     terminate with an error message. A number of new errors have been added
     since the manual was printed for reporting these types of errors. A list
     of these new errors follows:

     Configuration Processing Errors
     -------------------------------
     DOS/4G error (4000): configuration syntax error
          Section %s Option %s Value %s
     DOS/4G error (4001): configuration syntax error
         invalid section name                      Section %s
     DOS/4G error (4002): configuration syntax error
         zero length option string found           Section %s
     DOS/4G error (4003): configuration syntax error
         invalid option string found               Section %s Option %s
     DOS/4G error (4004): configuration syntax error
         option string not followed by '=' or ':'  Section %s Option %s Char %s

     Note: The configuration error numbers conflict with the GLU error
     numbers. The conflict was noticed too late for modification for this
     release but will be fixed in a future release. (Updated for 2.01 see 
     above)

     VM Processing Errors
     ---------------------
     DOS/4G error (2535): not enough physical memory (PhysLeave(%ldK) >
         Physical Available(%ldK))
     DOS/4G error (2536): logical error (PhysMin(%ldK) > PhysMax(%ldK))
     DOS/4G error (2537): logical error (SwapMin(%ldK) > SwapMax(%ldK))

C ** The configuration options PHYSMIN, PHYSLEAVE, SWAPMIN, and SWAPLEAVE
     are handled by DOS/4G as unmodifiable user requirements, whereas PHYSMAX
     and SWAPMAX represent upper limits that will not necessarily be reached
     during a given execution, but will in any case never be exceeded.

C ** There is a bug in the configuration manager which results in an
     erronious configuration error 4004 when a comment line is included
     inside of a either a [dos4g] or [dos4gvm] section in an ini file.
     The solution is not to use comments inside of these sections in
     your .ini file(s).

O ** DOS/4G v2.0 provides full NetBIOS support, with the exception of nowait
     NetBIOS interrupts.

M ** DPMI function 0009h (Set Descriptor Access Rights) requires that
     certain bit fields in the access and extended access rights/type bytes
     passed to this function be set to 0 or 1; in addition, the DPL field
     must equal the caller's CPL (determined most easily by performing an
     LAR instruction on the calling program's code segment).  See the DPMI
     specification.

M ** DPMI function 0102h (Resize DOS Memory Block) fails on requests to
     increase block size; requests to decrease block size succeed.

M ** DPMI functions 0600h/0601h (Lock/Unlock Linear Region), contrary to the
     description in the manual, return with the carry flag set when VM is not
     enabled.
